<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="subsec-calculating-ci" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Calculating confidence intervals in R-Instat</title>
    <p>
        R-Instat provides a straightforward way to calculate confidence intervals for the mean without
        writing any R code. In this section, we continue using the
        <c>work</c> dataset from the <c>lsrdata</c> package.
    </p>
    <p>
        In the dialog, select the <c>Customised</c> tab, choose the
        <c>hours</c> variable, and include the summary statistics required for your
        analysis. Ensure that the options for the sample mean and the confidence interval
        for the mean are selected. The default confidence level is 95%, although this can
        be changed if required.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-ci-mean-dialog">
        <caption>
            Calculating a confidence interval for the mean using the
            <c>One Variable Summarise</c> dialog.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ciMeanDialog.png"/>
    </figure>

    <p>
        After selecting <c>OK</c>, R-Instat displays the requested summary
        statistics together with the confidence interval for the mean.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-ci-mean-output">
        <caption>
            Output showing the sample mean together with its confidence interval.
        </caption>
        <image source="images/ciMeanOutput.png"/>
    </figure>

    <p>
        The confidence interval provides a range of plausible values for the population
        mean. Narrower intervals indicate more precise estimates, while wider intervals
        reflect greater uncertainty. The width of the interval depends primarily on the
        variability in the data and the sample size. Larger samples generally produce
        narrower confidence intervals because they provide more precise estimates of the
        population mean.
    </p>

    <p>
        Throughout this book, R-Instat will automatically calculate confidence intervals
        whenever they are available for the selected analysis. This allows you to focus on
        interpreting the results rather than performing the calculations manually.
    </p>
</subsection>